    <title>Combined summary - A Proposed Compromise to the Block Size Limit</title>
    <updated>2023-06-10T01:27:29.453002+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-July/009374.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The context discusses various aspects of the Bitcoin network and its scalability, including the Lightning Network, block size limits, global consensus, and fee markets. The Lightning Network is proposed as a way to scale Bitcoin while maintaining trustlessness and decentralization. Discussions also include concerns about centralization and the need for decentralized solutions. Off-chain solutions like hub-and-spoke payment channels and the Lightning Network are discussed as ways to use on-chain transactions more efficiently, but they are not considered global network consensus networks. The need for global consensus technology in Bitcoin to meet demand effectively is emphasized, and better scaling algorithms are being developed. Lastly, the comparison is made between the Bitcoin fee market and other financial markets that also lack assured quality of service.Bitcoin developers, including Adam Back and Mark Friedenbach, have engaged in email conversations about the Lightning Network as a potential solution to scaling Bitcoin. While some believe that the Lightning Network could solve the issue of long-lived payment endpoints, others like Gavin Andresen are concerned about centralization and security issues related to using hubs. Michael Naber suggests that a test should be conducted to increase the block size to 8 MB to meet the demand for a low-fee global consensus network while ensuring small miners remain profitable. However, there are concerns about constraining the capacity of Bitcoin Core below technological limits and driving users to seek solutions elsewhere. Payment channels and other systems are useful but do not meet the definition of global consensus. The Lightning Network is still in its early stages and is not resistant to a Sybil attack. Ultimately, the goal of Bitcoin Core is to provide the best solution possible to the global consensus problem while improving decentralization and throughput short-term and working on algorithmic improvements mid-term.In discussions about scaling Bitcoin, there is a debate between increasing block size and implementing off-chain solutions such as the Lightning Network. While off-chain systems like Changetip can enable economic transactions without blockchain transactions, they do not exhibit global network consensus. The Lightning Network proposes a solution to scalability by allowing participants in the network to send or receive coins through various hub connections via atomic transactions, but there are concerns about centralization pressure and complexity reduction. It is suggested that solutions should preserve Bitcoin's global consensus functionality and build trust-based systems on top of it. There is a demand for a low-fee global consensus network using blockchain technology, and market forces make it almost certain that the demand will be met by a blockchain with adequate capacity, whether it is Bitcoin Core or a fork. Bitcoin Core must remain the best solution possible to the global consensus problem, and constraining the block size below technological limits is a threat to its survival. Instead, the block size limit should be manually increased as demand occurs, except in the special case where increasing the limit would cause an undue burden upon users wishing to validate the integrity of the blockchain. A reasonable path forward could be to raise the block size to a static 8MB now, with a plan to increase it further should demand necessitate, except in the special case mentioned above.The article discusses several email conversations between individuals in the Bitcoin community regarding the block size limit and the scalability of the blockchain. Michael Naber argues that to ensure the survival of Bitcoin Core, it must remain a low-fee, high-capacity, secure, distributed, and fast solution. He suggests manually increasing the block size limit as demand occurs, except in cases where it would cause an undue burden upon users wishing to validate the integrity of the blockchain. Naber proposes raising the block size to a static 8MB now, with a plan to increase it further should demand necessitate, except in special cases. Adam Back notes that half the parameters listed by Michael Naber are in conflict with each other and suggests improving decentralization and throughput short-term while people work on algorithmic improvements mid-term. In another conversation, Benjamin expresses doubts about the Bitcoin system's capacity and how it works. He argues that there is no supply and demand in the system which would allow users to adapt fees and get different qualities of service depending on current capacity. Peter Todd rebuts this claim by stating that the Bitcoin system already works in that way. The system has fixed capacity where access is mediated by supply and demand transaction fees. This means that during peak load times, the fees are higher and users delay transactions to smooth out demand.The context discusses the scaling of Bitcoin and the block size limit. Jameson Lopp and Peter Todd had a discussion about Bitcoin scaling, where Lopp argued that for Bitcoin to scale, the number of validation nodes has to remain constant with the number of users, while Todd argued that it is better to preserve its global consensus functionality and build a trust-based system on top of it. The Lightning Network and Duplex Micropayment Channel papers explain layer 2 technology, which constitutes an early stage layer 2, and some of them even have on-chain netting and scale faster than the block-chain. Increasing the block size limit should be done manually as demand occurs</summary>
